==Signs and symptoms==
Bite wounds raise a number of [[medical]] concerns for the [[physician]] or [[first aid]]er including:

*Generalized tissue damage due to tearing and scratching.
*Serious [[hemorrhage]] if major blood vessels are pierced.
*[[Infection]] by [[bacterium|bacteria]] or other [[pathogen]]s, including [[rabies]].
*Introduction of [[Venom (poison)|venom]] into the wound by venomous animals such as some [[snakes]].
*Introduction of other irritants into the wound, causing [[inflammation]] and [[itching]].

===Treatment===
Bite wounds should be cleaned and [[Debridement|debrided]] as necessary but not closed. [[Ampicillin/sulbactam]] is indicated as [[HACEK endocarditis]], specifically ''Eikenella'', is the most worrying complication. A punctate wound over a joint surface should be regarded as an [[open joint injury]] until proven otherwise.

==Treatment==
Bite wounds are washed, ideally with povidone-iodine soap and water.  The injury is then loosely bandaged, but is not sutured due to risk of infection.

===Antibiotics===
Antibiotics prophylaxis is recommended for dog and cat bites of the hand<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bestbets.org/bets/bet.php?id=1021 |title=BestBets: Antibiotics in cat bites |format= |work= |accessdate=}}</ref> and human bites if they are more than superficial.<ref name="Oehler2009">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/S1473-3099(09)70110-0|author=Oehler RL, Velez AP, Mizrachi M, Lamarche J, Gompf S|title=Bite-related and septic syndrome caused by cats and dogs|journal=Lancet Infect Dis|year=2009|volume=9|pages=439&ndash;47|pmid=19555903|issue=7}}</ref>  Evidence for the need for antibiotic prophylaxis for bites in other areas inconclusive.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Medeiros I, Saconato H |title=Antibiotic prophylaxis for mammalian bites |journal=Cochrane Database Syst Rev |volume= |issue=2 |pages=CD001738 |year=2001 |pmid=11406003 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD001738 |url= |editor1-last=Medeiros |editor1-first=Iara Marques}}</ref>

For [[empirical therapy]], the first choice is [[amoxicillin with clavulanic acid]], and if the person is penicillin allergy [[doxycycline]] and [[metronidazole]].<ref name="Oehler2009"/>  The anti-staphylococcal penicillins (e.g., [[cloxacillin]], [[nafcillin]], [[flucloxacillin]]) and the [[macrolide]]s (e.g., [[erythromycin]], [[clarithromycin]]) are not used for empirical therapy, because they do not cover [[Pasteurella]] species.<ref name="Oehler2009"/>

===Rabies===
Animal bites inflicted by some animals, including [[carnivora]]ns and [[bat]]s can transmit [[rabies]]. The animal is caught alive or dead with its head preserved, so the head can later be analyzed to detect the disease. Signs of rabies include foaming at the mouth, self-mutilation, growling, jerky behavior, and red eyes. 

If the animal cannot be captured, prophylactic rabies treatment is recommended in most places. Certain places, such as [[Hawaii]], [[Australia]] and the [[United Kingdom]], are known not to have native rabies. Treatment is generally available in [[North America]] and the [[Northern European]] states.

===Tetanus===
[[Tetanus toxoid]] is indicated for virtually any bite that punctures the epidermis and [[tetanus immune globulin]] is indicated in patients with more than 10 years since prior vaccination. Tetanus boosters (Td) should be given every ten years.

